cs.DB, cs.DS, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.IT. 

The paper discusses a method for lexicographically sorting databases and nested data, which suggests it could belong to the cs.DB (databases) sub-category. The use of stable sorts and sorting algorithms also suggests it could belong to the cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-category. The application to Bayesian network scoring suggests it could belong to the cs.AI (artificial intelligence) sub-category. The performance analysis and running time analysis suggest it could belong to the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category. Finally, the use of pre-processing steps and refinement of sorts suggests it could belong to the cs.IT (information theory) sub-category.
